[[Image:Nimbus ozone Brewer-Dobson circulation.jpg|right]]
'''Brewer–Dobson circulation''' is a [[Model (abstract)|model]] of atmospheric circulation, proposed by [[Alan West Brewer|Alan Brewer]] in 1949 and [[Gordon Dobson]] in 1956, which attempts to explain why tropical air has less [[ozone]] than polar air, even though the tropical [[stratosphere]] is where most atmospheric ozone is produced. It is a simple circulation model that posits the existence of a slow [[Air current|current]] in the winter [[Sphere|hemisphere]] which redistributes air from the tropics to the extratropics.  The Brewer–Dobson circulation is driven by [[atmospheric waves]]<ref>{{citation| url=http://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/abs/10.1175/1520-0469%281990%29047%3C0392%3AOTGEOM%3E2.0.CO%3B2 | title= On the Global Exchange of Mass between the Stratosphere and Troposphere|author = J.R. Holton }}</ref> and may be speeding up due to climate change.<ref>{{citation| url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v410/n6830/abs/410799a0.html | title=Removal of chlorofluorocarbons by increased mass exchange between the stratosphere and troposphere in a changing climate |author = N.Butchart and A.A. Scaife}}</ref>

