{{Infobox Painting | image_file = Jacopo Tintoretto - Christ at the Sea of Galilee - WGA22616.jpg | alt= | image_size = | title = Christ at the Sea of Galilee | artist = [[Tintoretto|Jacopo Tintoretto]] | year = 1570s | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[canvas]] | height_metric = 117.1 | width_metric = 169.2 | museum = [[National Gallery of Art]] }}
'''''Christ at the Sea of Galilee''''' is an [[oil painting]] by [[Tintoretto|Jacopo Tintoretto]]. The painting depicts [[Jesus|Jesus Christ]] raises a hand toward the [[apostles]], who appear in a boat amid hostile waves at sea. It is an example of [[mannerism]],<ref>{{cite web| title=Christ at the Sea of Galilee| accessdate=2018-04-17| publisher=Aaron Art Prints| url=http://www.aaronartprints.org/tintoretto-christattheseaofgalilee.php}}</ref> a European art style that exaggerates proportion and favors compositional tension. This can be seen in the expressive postures of the figures and the muted, yet intense color of the sea and sky.
Tintoretto had a mostly [[Venice|Venetian]] audience and was known for painting scenes of Venice, but this painting departs from this path. Additionally, the scene was made to look overly dramatic rather than realistic. The paint is thin and Tintoretto uses extreme highlights, intensifying the darkness and light that seems to come from a compressed and directed light source.<ref>{{cite book| last=Muhlberger| first=Richard| title=The Bible in Art: The New Testament| publisher=New York: Portland House| year=1990| pages=82-83}}</ref>
The painting is currently on display in the Samuel H. Kress Collection at the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=nga>{{cite web| title=National Gallery of Art| publisher=National Gallery of Art| url=https://www.nga.gov/collection/art-object-page.41637.html| accessdate=2018-04-17}}</ref>
